<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-04-19T17:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-04-19T17:00:00-05:00" n="21" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d21">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">894c.111/2: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to
                                the Minister in China</hi> (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">Reinsch</hi></persName>)</head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-04-19T18:00:00-04:00"><hi rend="italic">April 19,
                                        1918—6 p.m.</hi></date></dateline></opener>
                        <p>Your April 6, 7 p.m.</p>
                        <p>The Department acquiesces in the application of the passport regulations,
                            made temporarily expedient by the war, to Americans <pb facs="0134" n="34" xml:id="pg_34"/> entering Port Arthur leased territory and
                            South Manchuria railroad zone on the understanding that acquiescence
                            does not commit this Government in any respect regarding the relative
                            rights of China and Japan in these districts or regarding the divestment
                            of American citizens in Manchuria of their extraterritorial rights.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Lansing</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>